SECTION 1: SOFT DELETE VS HARD DELETE STRATEGY
================================================================================

1.1 DECISION: SOFT DELETE WITH SCHEDULED HARD DELETE (HYBRID)

Use soft delete for ALL user-facing entities (tasks, projects, subtasks, comments,
attachments). Never use hard delete at the application layer. Hard delete occurs
only through a scheduled garbage collection process.

Rationale:
- Sync requires tombstone records to propagate deletions to offline devices
- Undo/restore is a core UX feature for a productivity app
- Audit trails are required for team collaboration features
- DPDP Act 2023 compliance requires deletion capability (but on user request, not immediate)
- Figma, Linear, Todoist, Notion all use soft delete as the primary mechanism

1.2 SCHEMA CHANGES REQUIRED

Add these columns to EVERY syncable table (tasks, projects, subtasks, comments,
labels, attachments):

    deleted_at          TIMESTAMPTZ     NULL        -- NULL = not deleted
    deleted_by          UUID            NULL        -- FK to profiles.id
    deletion_type       TEXT            NULL        -- 'user' | 'cascade' | 'system' | 'admin'
    restore_deadline    TIMESTAMPTZ     NULL        -- after this, eligible for hard delete

Do NOT use a boolean is_deleted flag. A timestamp is strictly superior because:
- It enables "show me what was deleted in the last 7 days"
- It serves as the tombstone marker for sync
- It enables time-based garbage collection queries
- It doubles as an audit field

Add a sync metadata table:

    CREATE TABLE sync_tombstones (
        id              UUID PRIMARY KEY,
        entity_type     TEXT NOT NULL,           -- 'task', 'project', etc.
        entity_id       UUID NOT NULL,
        deleted_at      TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL,
        deleted_by      UUID REFERENCES profiles(id),
        purged_at       TIMESTAMPTZ NULL,        -- when hard-deleted
        metadata        JSONB NULL               -- snapshot of key fields for undo
    );

    CREATE INDEX idx_tombstones_entity ON sync_tombstones(entity_type, entity_id);
    CREATE INDEX idx_tombstones_purge ON sync_tombstones(purged_at) WHERE purged_at IS NULL;

1.3 TOMBSTONE LIFECYCLE

    Phase 1: SOFT DELETE (immediate)
    - Set deleted_at = NOW()
    - Set restore_deadline = NOW() + retention_period
    - Store minimal snapshot in sync_tombstones.metadata (title, project_id, parent_id)
    - Tombstone syncs to all connected clients via WebSocket delta
    - Tombstone syncs to offline clients on next pull

    Phase 2: RECYCLE BIN (0-30 days, configurable per plan)
    - Free tier: 7-day retention
    - Pro tier: 30-day retention
    - Team tier: 90-day retention
    - User can browse and restore deleted items
    - Deleted items excluded from all normal queries via WHERE deleted_at IS NULL

    Phase 3: HARD DELETE / GARBAGE COLLECTION (after retention expires)
    - Scheduled job runs every 6 hours
    - Selects records WHERE restore_deadline < NOW() AND purged_at IS NULL
    - Performs hard DELETE from the entity table
    - Sets purged_at = NOW() on the sync_tombstone record
    - Tombstone record itself is retained for 90 more days (so late-syncing clients
      still learn about the deletion)

    Phase 4: TOMBSTONE PURGE (90 days after hard delete)
    - Tombstone records with purged_at < NOW() - 90 days are hard deleted
    - If a client has not synced in 90+ days, it must perform a full sync (not incremental)

1.4 QUERY PATTERNS

Every query against syncable tables MUST include the soft-delete filter.
Enforce this at the repository layer, not the query layer.

    -- Standard query (excludes deleted)
    SELECT * FROM tasks WHERE user_id = $1 AND deleted_at IS NULL;

    -- Recycle bin query
    SELECT * FROM tasks WHERE user_id = $1 AND deleted_at IS NOT NULL AND restore_deadline > NOW();

    -- Sync pull query (includes deleted for tombstone propagation)
    SELECT * FROM tasks WHERE user_id = $1 AND updated_at > $lastSyncTimestamp;
    -- NOTE: sync pulls MUST include soft-deleted records so clients learn about deletions

1.5 UNIQUE CONSTRAINT HANDLING

Problem: If a user deletes a project named "Work" then creates a new project named
"Work", a unique constraint on (user_id, name) would fail.

Solution: Include deleted_at in unique constraints, or use partial unique indexes:

    CREATE UNIQUE INDEX idx_projects_unique_name
    ON projects (user_id, name)
    WHERE deleted_at IS NULL;

This allows multiple soft-deleted records with the same name while preventing
duplicates among active records.

================================================================================
SECTION 2: CONFLICT MATRIX
================================================================================

2.0 CLOCK STRATEGY: HYBRID LOGICAL CLOCK (HLC)

CRITICAL: Replace raw DateTime timestamps with Hybrid Logical Clocks throughout the
sync system. The current implementation uses DateTime which is vulnerable to clock
skew between devices.

HLC Structure:
    {
        wallTime: int64,    // Physical clock (milliseconds since epoch)
        counter:  int16,    // Logical counter (0-65535)
        nodeId:   string    // Unique device/server identifier
    }

HLC is a 64-bit value: 48 bits for wall time + 16 bits for counter.
Node ID is stored separately and used only for tie-breaking.

Algorithm:
    On local event:
        if wallClock > hlc.wallTime:
            hlc = { wallTime: wallClock, counter: 0 }
        else:
            hlc = { wallTime: hlc.wallTime, counter: hlc.counter + 1 }

    On receiving remote HLC:
        maxWall = max(wallClock, hlc.wallTime, remote.wallTime)
        if maxWall == hlc.wallTime == remote.wallTime:
            counter = max(hlc.counter, remote.counter) + 1
        elif maxWall == hlc.wallTime:
            counter = hlc.counter + 1
        elif maxWall == remote.wallTime:
            counter = remote.counter + 1
        else:
            counter = 0
        hlc = { wallTime: maxWall, counter: counter }

Why HLC over Vector Clocks:
- Vector clocks grow linearly with number of devices (problematic for team sync)
- HLC is constant-size (64 bits) regardless of participant count
- HLC preserves causality like logical clocks
- HLC stays close to real wall-clock time (useful for UI display)
- Used in production by CockroachDB, MongoDB, YugabyteDB

Why HLC over raw timestamps:
- Two events on the same device within the same millisecond get distinct ordering
- Causality is preserved: if device A sends to device B, B's subsequent events
  are guaranteed to have higher HLC values than A's sent event
- Moderate clock drift (seconds) is tolerated without incorrect ordering

Server-side drift guard:
    On receiving a client HLC, the server checks:
    if abs(client.wallTime - server.wallClock) > MAX_DRIFT (e.g., 60 seconds):
        reject the operation with error "Clock drift too high, please sync device clock"
    This prevents malicious or misconfigured clients from poisoning the timeline.

2.1 SCENARIO: SAME-FIELD EDIT CONFLICT
    User A edits task title to "Buy groceries" (offline)
    User B edits same task title to "Buy vegetables" (offline)
    Both come online.

    Resolution: FIELD-LEVEL LWW
    - Compare HLC timestamps on the "title" field from both versions
    - Higher HLC wins
    - If HLCs are identical (near-impossible with node ID), server version wins (server authority tiebreaker)
    - The losing edit is logged to a conflict_log table for potential manual review

    Conflict Log Entry:
    {
        entity_type: "task",
        entity_id: "uuid-xxx",
        field: "title",
        winner_value: "Buy vegetables",
        winner_hlc: "1709913600000:0003:device-B",
        loser_value: "Buy groceries",
        loser_hlc: "1709913590000:0001:device-A",
        resolved_at: "2026-03-09T10:00:00Z",
        resolution: "lww_auto"
    }

    UX: Show a subtle toast notification: "A conflict was resolved on 'Buy vegetables'.
    Tap to view." User can then see both versions and override if needed.

    CURRENT IMPLEMENTATION STATUS: Already handled correctly by LwwResolver.merge()
    in the existing codebase. The field-level comparison at lines 83-99 of
    lww_resolver.dart handles this. Needs HLC upgrade.

2.2 SCENARIO: DELETE-EDIT CONFLICT
    User A deletes task "Buy groceries"
    User B edits same task's description to "Get organic items" (offline)
    B comes online after A.

    Resolution: UPDATE-WINS (RESURRECT)

    CRITICAL DESIGN DECISION: Use UPDATE-WINS, not DELETE-WINS.

    Rationale for update-wins in a productivity app:
    - Data loss is worse than seeing a "deleted" item reappear
    - The editing user clearly intended for the task to exist (they were working on it)
    - Undo is always available if the resurrection is unwanted
    - Todoist, Linear, and Notion all prefer preserving data over honoring deletes
    - The deleting user can simply delete again with one tap

    Algorithm:
    1. Server receives B's edit for task that A already soft-deleted
    2. Server detects: incoming operation targets a soft-deleted entity
    3. Server checks: is the edit's HLC > the deletion's HLC?
       - YES: Resurrect the entity (clear deleted_at), apply the edit, notify A
       - NO: Delete wins (the edit was made before the delete, user just synced late)
    4. If resurrected, push a delta to A: "Task 'Buy groceries' was restored by
       a concurrent edit from another device/user"

    CHANGE REQUIRED IN EXISTING CODE:
    The current LwwResolver (lines 25-31) unconditionally lets remote delete win
    over local non-deleted. This must be changed to compare HLC timestamps:

    CURRENT (WRONG for update-wins):
        if (remote.isDeleted && !local.isDeleted) {
            return MergeResult(record: remote.markSynced(), outcome: remoteWins);
        }

    SHOULD BE:
        if (remote.isDeleted && !local.isDeleted) {
            // Compare the deletion timestamp against the latest edit timestamp
            if (remote.updatedAt.isAfter(local.updatedAt)) {
                return MergeResult(record: remote.markSynced(), outcome: remoteWins);
            } else {
                // Edit is newer than delete — resurrect
                return MergeResult(record: local, outcome: localWins);
                // Server will also need to clear deleted_at on the server record
            }
        }

2.3 SCENARIO: MOVE-MOVE CONFLICT (DIFFERENT PROJECTS)
    User A moves task from Inbox to "Project X"
    User B moves same task from Inbox to "Project Y" (offline)
    Both come online.

    Resolution: FIELD-LEVEL LWW on the "project_id" field.
    - project_id is just another field with its own HLC timestamp
    - Higher HLC wins, task ends up in that project
    - Loser's move is logged to conflict_log
    - Notify the losing user: "Task was moved to Project X by [User A]"
    - No special handling needed beyond standard field-level LWW

    Edge case — cascading project permissions:
    If User B does not have access to Project X (where the task ended up),
    the task should still move to Project X, but User B should be notified:
    "This task was moved to a project you don't have access to."
    The task disappears from B's view (access control filter removes it).

2.4 SCENARIO: COMPLETE-THEN-ADD-SUBTASK CONFLICT
    User A completes task (status = "completed", completedAt = timestamp)
    User B adds a subtask to the same task (offline)
    Both come online.

    Resolution: BOTH OPERATIONS APPLY (NO TRUE CONFLICT)
    - "status" and "completedAt" are fields on the parent task
    - A new subtask is a CREATE operation on a child entity
    - These are independent operations — no field-level conflict exists
    - Result: Task is marked completed AND has the new subtask
    - The UX should show: "Task completed, but has an incomplete subtask"
    - Optionally: auto-reopen the parent task if it has incomplete subtasks
      (this is a business rule, not a sync rule)

    Business rule recommendation:
    When a completed task receives a new incomplete subtask, automatically
    set the parent task's status back to "in_progress" and clear completedAt.
    This preserves the intent of both users: A thought the work was done,
    B added more work, so the task should reflect that it's not done.

2.5 SCENARIO: DELETE-PROJECT WITH TASK-ADD CONFLICT
    User A deletes "Project Alpha" (soft delete, cascades to tasks)
    User B adds a new task to "Project Alpha" (offline)
    Both come online.

    Resolution: MULTI-STEP RESOLUTION

    Step 1: B's task arrives at server referencing a soft-deleted project
    Step 2: Server detects: task.project_id references a deleted project
    Step 3: Decision tree:
        a) If B's task creation HLC > project deletion HLC:
           RESURRECT the project (and all its cascade-deleted tasks)
           Apply B's new task to the restored project
           Notify A: "Project Alpha was restored because [User B] added a task to it"

        b) If B's task creation HLC < project deletion HLC:
           B's task was created before the delete (just synced late)
           Move B's task to Inbox (set project_id = NULL)
           Notify B: "Your task was moved to Inbox because Project Alpha was deleted"
           Record in conflict_log

    Why resurrect (option a):
    - B clearly thought the project existed and was working on it
    - Creating a task is higher-intent than deleting a project
    - The alternative (silently orphaning or discarding the task) causes data loss
    - A can re-delete the project if they still want it gone

    Cascade resurrection algorithm:
    When resurrecting a project:
    1. Clear deleted_at on the project
    2. Clear deleted_at on all tasks WHERE project_id = project.id
       AND deletion_type = 'cascade' (not user-initiated deletes)
    3. Do NOT resurrect tasks that were individually deleted by users
       (deletion_type = 'user'), only those cascade-deleted with the project

2.6 SCENARIO: DIFFERENT-FIELD EDIT (NO CONFLICT)
    User A changes task priority to "high"
    User B changes same task's due_date to "2026-03-15" (offline)
    Both come online.

    Resolution: AUTOMATIC MERGE — NO CONFLICT
    - priority and due_date are different fields
    - Each has its own HLC timestamp
    - Both changes apply cleanly
    - Result: priority = "high" AND due_date = "2026-03-15"
    - No notification needed
    - This is the most common case and should be the fast path

    CURRENT IMPLEMENTATION STATUS: Already handled correctly by the field-level
    LWW merge loop in lww_resolver.dart (lines 64-100). Each field is compared
    independently. No changes needed for this scenario.

2.7 SCENARIO: SAME-USER MULTI-DEVICE CREATE
    Device A creates task "Call dentist" (offline)
    Device B creates task "Call dentist" (offline, same user, different device)
    Both come online.

    Resolution: BOTH TASKS ARE CREATED (NO DEDUP BY CONTENT)

    Rationale:
    - Each task has a unique UUID generated client-side
    - Different UUIDs = different entities, regardless of content similarity
    - Deduplicating by content would be dangerous (user may genuinely want two
      tasks with the same title)
    - This is how Todoist, Linear, and Notion handle it

    Client-side UUID generation:
    - Use UUIDv7 (time-ordered, sortable) not UUIDv4 (random)
    - UUIDv7 embeds a timestamp, making database indexing more efficient
    - Format: timestamp_ms (48 bits) + random (74 bits) + version (6 bits)
    - Collision probability: effectively zero for practical purposes

    Post-sync UX:
    - If the system detects two tasks with identical titles created within a
      short window (< 5 minutes) by the same user, show a gentle prompt:
      "You have two similar tasks: 'Call dentist'. Want to merge them?"
    - This is a suggestion, not automatic — user decides

2.8 SCENARIO: CONCURRENT FIELD EDIT + FIELD DELETE
    User A sets task.description = "Important notes here"
    User B sets task.description = NULL (clears it) (offline)
    Both come online.

    Resolution: FIELD-LEVEL LWW (NULL is a valid value)
    - NULL is treated as a legitimate field value, not as absence
    - Compare HLC timestamps on the "description" field
    - Higher HLC wins, even if the winning value is NULL
    - This correctly handles intentional field clearing

2.9 SCENARIO: REORDER CONFLICT (SORT ORDER)
    User A reorders tasks in a project: [T1, T2, T3] -> [T3, T1, T2]
    User B reorders same tasks: [T1, T2, T3] -> [T2, T3, T1] (offline)
    Both come online.

    Resolution: LWW ON INDIVIDUAL sort_order FIELDS

    Each task has its own sort_order field. Reordering updates sort_order on
    multiple tasks. Field-level LWW applies independently per task:

    - T1.sort_order: A set to 1, B set to 2 -> higher HLC wins
    - T2.sort_order: A set to 2, B set to 0 -> higher HLC wins
    - T3.sort_order: A set to 0, B set to 1 -> higher HLC wins

    This may result in a "mixed" order that neither user intended. This is
    acceptable because:
    - Reordering conflicts are rare in practice
    - The result is still a valid ordering
    - Either user can re-sort with one drag-and-drop

    ADVANCED ALTERNATIVE (Phase 3+): Use fractional indexing instead of integers
    for sort_order. This avoids the need to update multiple records when
    reordering. A task inserted between items with sort 0.5 and 0.75 gets
    sort 0.625. Only one record is updated per move.

2.10 SCENARIO: RECURRING TASK RRULE CONFLICT
    User A changes recurrence from "daily" to "weekly"
    User B changes recurrence from "daily" to "monthly" (offline)
    Both come online.

    Resolution: FIELD-LEVEL LWW on the "rrule" field.
    - RRULE is stored as a single text field (RFC 5545 string)
    - Standard LWW applies — higher HLC wins
    - No partial merge of RRULE components (it's atomic)

2.11 FULL CONFLICT MATRIX SUMMARY TABLE

    Scenario                        | Resolution          | Winner         | Notify?
    --------------------------------|---------------------|----------------|--------
    Same field, same entity         | Field-level LWW     | Higher HLC     | Toast
    Different fields, same entity   | Auto-merge          | Both apply     | No
    Edit vs Delete (edit newer)     | Update-wins         | Edit (resurrect)| Yes
    Edit vs Delete (delete newer)   | Delete-wins         | Delete         | Yes
    Move to Project X vs Y          | LWW on project_id   | Higher HLC     | Toast
    Complete vs Add subtask         | Both apply          | Both           | Optional
    Delete project vs Add task      | Resurrect if newer  | Task/Project   | Yes
    Same-user multi-device create   | Both created        | Both           | Suggest merge
    Field set vs Field clear (NULL) | Field-level LWW     | Higher HLC     | No
    Reorder vs Reorder              | Per-task LWW        | Mixed          | No
    RRULE change vs RRULE change    | Field-level LWW     | Higher HLC     | Toast
    Label add vs Label remove       | LWW on labels field | Higher HLC     | No

================================================================================
SECTION 3: TEAM SYNC SCENARIOS
================================================================================

3.1 SYNC SCOPE AND VISIBILITY MODEL

Data is scoped into three visibility levels:

    PRIVATE:    Only the owner can see/edit. Synced only to owner's devices.
    SHARED:     All team members with project access can see. Synced to all members.
    PUBLIC:     All team members can see (read-only for non-members).

Sync scope determines WHAT data flows to WHICH devices:

    Entity          | Sync Scope
    ----------------|------------------------------------------
    Personal task   | Owner's devices only
    Shared project  | All members with project access
    Task in shared  | All members with project access
    project         |
    Comment         | All members who can see the parent task
    Attachment      | All members who can see the parent task
    User profile    | Public fields to all team members
    Team settings   | All team admins

3.2 ROLE-BASED SYNC PERMISSIONS

    Role        | Create  | Read    | Update Own | Update Others | Delete  | Manage Members
    ------------|---------|---------|------------|---------------|---------|---------------
    Owner       | Yes     | All     | Yes        | Yes           | All     | Yes
    Admin       | Yes     | All     | Yes        | Yes           | All     | Yes
    Manager     | Yes     | All     | Yes        | Assigned only | Own     | Invite only
    Member      | Yes     | All     | Yes        | No            | Own     | No
    Viewer      | No      | All     | No         | No            | No      | No
    Guest       | No      | Shared  | No         | No            | No      | No

Sync permission enforcement happens at THREE levels:

    Level 1 - SERVER PUSH FILTER:
    When broadcasting a delta via WebSocket, the server checks: does the
    recipient have read access to this entity? If not, skip.

    Level 2 - CLIENT PULL FILTER:
    When a client pulls changes, the server query includes access control:
    SELECT * FROM tasks
    WHERE updated_at > $lastSync
    AND (user_id = $userId
         OR project_id IN (SELECT project_id FROM project_members WHERE user_id = $userId))
    AND deleted_at IS NULL OR (deleted_at IS NOT NULL AND updated_at > $lastSync);

    Level 3 - CLIENT-SIDE ENFORCEMENT:
    Even if a record somehow reaches a client that shouldn't have it (race condition),
    the client checks access before displaying. Defense in depth.

3.3 SHARED PROJECT SYNC FLOW

    User A creates a shared project and invites User B:

    1. Server creates project record with is_shared = true
    2. Server creates project_members record: { project_id, user_id: B, role: 'member' }
    3. Server sends WebSocket delta to B: "You were added to Project Alpha"
    4. B's client receives delta, stores project locally, begins syncing tasks
    5. B's client pulls all tasks for the project (initial sync for that project)

    User B creates a task in the shared project (offline):

    1. Task is created locally with project_id = shared_project_id
    2. Task is queued for sync with needsSync = true
    3. When B comes online, task is pushed to server
    4. Server validates: does B have create permission for this project? Yes.
    5. Server stores task, assigns server HLC
    6. Server broadcasts delta to all project members (including A)
    7. A's client receives delta, stores task locally

3.4 TEAM MEMBER REMOVAL SYNC

    When User A (admin) removes User B from a shared project:

    1. Server soft-deletes the project_members record
    2. Server sends WebSocket delta to B: "You were removed from Project Alpha"
    3. B's client receives delta
    4. B's client marks all locally-cached data for that project as "access_revoked"
    5. B's client removes the data from local DB (hard delete locally — B has no right
       to keep the data)
    6. Any pending sync operations from B for that project are discarded
    7. If B has offline edits for that project that haven't synced:
       - These are moved to a "rejected_operations" table locally
       - User is notified: "Your edits to [Project Alpha] could not be saved because
         you were removed from the project"
       - Optionally: offer to save the edits as personal tasks in Inbox

3.5 PERMISSION CHANGE MID-SYNC

    User B is downgraded from "Member" to "Viewer" while offline:

    1. B makes edits while offline (B thinks they're still a Member)
    2. B comes online, pushes edits
    3. Server rejects the writes with error code 403: "Insufficient permissions"
    4. B's client receives rejections
    5. For each rejected operation:
       - Mark the local record as "sync_rejected"
       - Revert the local change to match server state (pull the server version)
       - Notify user: "Your edit to [task] was rejected — your role changed to Viewer"
    6. B's client updates the cached role and adjusts the UI accordingly

3.6 CONCURRENT TEAM EDITS

    User A and User B both edit the same task in a shared project (both online):

    Real-time path (WebSocket):
    1. A makes an edit, sends delta to server
    2. Server applies edit, broadcasts to B within ~50ms
    3. B sees A's edit appear in real-time
    4. B makes their own edit (on a different field) — no conflict
    5. If B edits the same field, B's version overwrites A's (LWW, B is later)

    Offline path:
    1. Both A and B go offline and edit the same task
    2. Standard field-level LWW applies when both come online
    3. All team members receive the merged result

================================================================================
SECTION 4: DELETION HANDLING
================================================================================

4.1 CASCADE RULES

CRITICAL: Do NOT use database-level ON DELETE CASCADE for soft deletes.
Cascade soft-deletion must be handled at the APPLICATION level.

    Entity              | When Deleted, Cascade To:
    --------------------|------------------------------------------
    Project             | All tasks in project (cascade soft delete)
                        | All task comments (cascade soft delete)
                        | All task attachments (cascade soft delete)
                        | All project members (cascade soft delete)
                        | Project labels (cascade soft delete)
    Task                | All subtasks (cascade soft delete)
                        | All comments on task (cascade soft delete)
                        | All attachments on task (cascade soft delete)
                        | All reminders for task (cascade soft delete)
    User Account        | All personal projects (cascade soft delete)
                        | All personal tasks (cascade soft delete)
                        | Membership records in shared projects (cascade soft delete)
                        | Tasks ASSIGNED to user in shared projects: set assignee_id = NULL
                        | (do NOT delete the tasks, just unassign)

    Cascade deletion algorithm (server-side):
    ```
    function cascadeSoftDelete(entityType, entityId, deletedBy, timestamp) {
        // 1. Soft-delete the entity itself
        update(entityType, entityId, {
            deleted_at: timestamp,
            deleted_by: deletedBy,
            deletion_type: 'user',
            restore_deadline: timestamp + RETENTION_PERIOD
        });

        // 2. Get cascade rules for this entity type
        const cascadeTargets = CASCADE_RULES[entityType];

        // 3. Soft-delete each cascade target
        for (const target of cascadeTargets) {
            const children = findByParent(target.entityType, target.foreignKey, entityId);
            for (const child of children) {
                if (child.deleted_at === null) {
                    update(target.entityType, child.id, {
                        deleted_at: timestamp,
                        deleted_by: deletedBy,
                        deletion_type: 'cascade',     // <-- marks as cascade, not user
                        restore_deadline: timestamp + RETENTION_PERIOD
                    });
                    // Recurse for nested cascades
                    cascadeSoftDelete(target.entityType, child.id, deletedBy, timestamp);
                }
            }
        }

        // 4. Create tombstone record
        insertTombstone(entityType, entityId, deletedBy, timestamp);

        // 5. Broadcast deletion delta to all affected clients
        broadcastDelta({
            type: 'delete',
            entityType,
            entityId,
            timestamp,
            cascadedIds: [...] // all cascade-deleted IDs for batch local processing
        });
    }
    ```

4.2 ORPHANED RECORD DETECTION AND CLEANUP

Orphaned records are entities whose parent was deleted but the cascade
didn't reach them (due to sync timing, bugs, or schema changes).

    Detection query (run daily):
    ```sql
    -- Tasks referencing non-existent or deleted projects
    SELECT t.id, t.title, t.project_id
    FROM tasks t
    LEFT JOIN projects p ON t.project_id = p.id
    WHERE t.deleted_at IS NULL
    AND t.project_id IS NOT NULL
    AND (p.id IS NULL OR p.deleted_at IS NOT NULL);

    -- Subtasks referencing non-existent or deleted parent tasks
    SELECT s.id, s.title, s.parent_task_id
    FROM subtasks s
    LEFT JOIN tasks t ON s.parent_task_id = t.id
    WHERE s.deleted_at IS NULL
    AND (t.id IS NULL OR t.deleted_at IS NOT NULL);
    ```

    Remediation:
    - Move orphaned tasks to Inbox (set project_id = NULL)
    - Move orphaned subtasks to top-level tasks (set parent_task_id = NULL)
    - Log the orphan detection for monitoring
    - Do NOT auto-delete orphans — they represent data the user may want

4.3 UNDO / RESTORE MECHANISM

    Single-entity restore:
    1. User selects item in Recycle Bin, taps "Restore"
    2. Client sends restore request to server
    3. Server clears deleted_at, deleted_by, deletion_type, restore_deadline
    4. Server broadcasts restore delta to all clients
    5. All clients clear the soft-delete fields locally

    Cascade restore (restoring a project restores its children):
    1. User restores a deleted project
    2. Server restores the project record
    3. Server finds all entities with deletion_type = 'cascade' that were deleted
       at the same timestamp (or within 1 second) with the same deleted_by
    4. Server restores ONLY cascade-deleted children, NOT individually-deleted children
       Example: If the project had 10 tasks, and 8 were cascade-deleted when the
       project was deleted, but 2 were deleted individually by users before that,
       only the 8 cascade-deleted tasks are restored.
    5. Server broadcasts restore deltas for all restored entities

    Undo (within 10-second window):
    1. After any delete operation, show an "Undo" toast for 10 seconds
    2. If user taps Undo within the window, perform immediate restore
    3. This is a client-side convenience — the actual mechanism is the same restore
    4. The 10-second undo uses a local operation ID, not the server restore flow,
       for instant responsiveness

    Conflict during restore:
    If User A deletes a task and User B restores it simultaneously, the standard
    update-wins resolution applies — the restore (which is an update clearing
    deleted_at) wins over the delete if its HLC is higher.

================================================================================
SECTION 5: SYNC QUEUE MANAGEMENT
================================================================================

5.1 LOCAL SYNC QUEUE SCHEMA (Drift/SQLite)

    CREATE TABLE sync_queue (
        id              TEXT PRIMARY KEY,       -- UUIDv7
        entity_type     TEXT NOT NULL,          -- 'task', 'project', etc.
        entity_id       TEXT NOT NULL,          -- UUID of the entity
        operation       TEXT NOT NULL,          -- 'create', 'update', 'delete'
        payload         TEXT NOT NULL,          -- JSON of changed fields + HLC timestamps
        hlc_timestamp   INTEGER NOT NULL,       -- HLC as 64-bit integer for ordering
        created_at      INTEGER NOT NULL,       -- local wall clock (for display)
        retry_count     INTEGER DEFAULT 0,      -- number of failed push attempts
        max_retries     INTEGER DEFAULT 10,     -- give up after this many
        status          TEXT DEFAULT 'pending', -- pending, processing, completed, failed, rejected
        error_message   TEXT,                   -- last error if failed
        batch_id        TEXT,                   -- group operations for atomic batch
        depends_on      TEXT,                   -- ID of operation this depends on (ordering)
        idempotency_key TEXT UNIQUE NOT NULL    -- prevents duplicate processing
    );

    CREATE INDEX idx_sync_queue_status ON sync_queue(status);
    CREATE INDEX idx_sync_queue_entity ON sync_queue(entity_type, entity_id);
    CREATE INDEX idx_sync_queue_depends ON sync_queue(depends_on) WHERE depends_on IS NOT NULL;

5.2 OPERATION ORDERING

Operations MUST be applied in causal order, not arbitrary order.

    Dependency rules:
    - CREATE must be processed before any UPDATE on the same entity
    - UPDATE must be processed before DELETE on the same entity
    - Parent CREATE must be processed before child CREATE
      (project before task, task before subtask)
    - These dependencies are expressed via the depends_on field

    Ordering algorithm:
    1. Topological sort of the sync queue by depends_on relationships
    2. Within independent operations, sort by hlc_timestamp (ascending)
    3. If a dependency is in "failed" status, hold dependent operations
    4. If a dependency is in "rejected" status, also reject dependents

    Example:
    Op1: CREATE project "Alpha"          depends_on: NULL
    Op2: CREATE task "Task 1" in Alpha   depends_on: Op1
    Op3: UPDATE task "Task 1" title      depends_on: Op2
    Op4: CREATE task "Task 2" in Alpha   depends_on: Op1
    Op5: DELETE task "Task 1"            depends_on: Op3

    Processing order: Op1 -> (Op2, Op4 in parallel) -> Op3 -> Op5

5.3 DEDUPLICATION

    Problem: If a sync attempt partially succeeds (network drops mid-batch),
    retrying might apply some operations twice.

    Solution: IDEMPOTENCY KEYS

    Every operation has a unique idempotency_key (UUIDv7 generated at operation
    creation time, NOT at sync time).

    Server-side:
    - Maintain a processed_operations table:
      { idempotency_key TEXT PRIMARY KEY, processed_at TIMESTAMPTZ, result JSONB }
    - Before processing any operation, check if idempotency_key exists
    - If exists: return the cached result (do not re-process)
    - If not: process the operation, store the result
    - Purge processed_operations older than 7 days

    Client-side content deduplication:
    - Before adding to sync queue, check: is there already a pending operation
      for the same entity_id and operation type?
    - If YES for UPDATE: merge the field changes into the existing queue entry
      (combine changed fields, take latest HLC per field)
    - If YES for DELETE: discard any pending UPDATE operations for the same entity
    - If YES for CREATE: this should never happen (UUID collision) — log error

5.4 RETRY LOGIC

    Strategy: Exponential backoff with jitter

    Base delay:    1 second
    Max delay:     5 minutes
    Multiplier:    2x
    Jitter:        +/- 30% random
    Max retries:   10 (then mark as "failed", require manual intervention)

    Retry schedule (approximate):
    Attempt 1:  1s    (+/- 0.3s jitter)
    Attempt 2:  2s    (+/- 0.6s)
    Attempt 3:  4s    (+/- 1.2s)
    Attempt 4:  8s    (+/- 2.4s)
    Attempt 5:  16s   (+/- 4.8s)
    Attempt 6:  32s   (+/- 9.6s)
    Attempt 7:  64s   (+/- 19.2s)
    Attempt 8:  128s  (+/- 38.4s)
    Attempt 9:  256s  (+/- 76.8s)
    Attempt 10: 300s  (capped at max, +/- 90s)

    Error classification:
    - 4xx errors (except 429): Do NOT retry. Mark as "rejected".
      These are permission errors, validation errors, etc.
    - 429 (rate limit): Retry with server-specified Retry-After header
    - 5xx errors: Retry with backoff
    - Network errors (timeout, connection refused): Retry with backoff
    - Conflict errors (409): Apply server's version, then retry with merged data

    After max retries:
    - Mark operation as "failed"
    - Show persistent notification: "Some changes couldn't be synced. Tap to retry."
    - Keep the operation in the queue indefinitely (never auto-discard user data)
    - Allow manual retry or manual discard

5.5 BATCH OPERATIONS

    Group related operations into atomic batches using batch_id.

    When to batch:
    - Cascade deletes (project + all its tasks)
    - Reorder operations (multiple sort_order updates)
    - Bulk edits (changing priority on 10 selected tasks)

    Batch behavior:
    - All operations in a batch are sent to the server in a single request
    - Server processes them in a transaction
    - If ANY operation in the batch fails, ALL are rolled back
    - Client retries the entire batch (not individual operations)
    - Exception: if a batch fails due to a single "rejected" operation,
      that operation is removed and the batch is retried without it

    Server batch endpoint:
    POST /api/v1/sync/batch
    Body: {
        batch_id: "uuid",
        operations: [
            { idempotency_key, entity_type, entity_id, operation, payload, hlc },
            ...
        ]
    }
    Response: {
        batch_id: "uuid",
        results: {
            "idempotency_key_1": { status: "ok", server_version: {...} },
            "idempotency_key_2": { status: "rejected", error: "..." },
        }
    }

5.6 SYNC QUEUE SIZE MANAGEMENT

    The sync queue can grow large if the user is offline for an extended period.

    Compaction rules (applied before sync):
    1. Multiple UPDATEs to the same entity: merge into a single UPDATE with all
       changed fields and latest HLC per field
    2. CREATE followed by UPDATEs: merge all updates into the CREATE payload
    3. CREATE followed by DELETE: remove both (entity never existed on server)
    4. UPDATE followed by DELETE: keep only the DELETE
    5. DELETE followed by CREATE (same entity_id): this shouldn't happen with UUIDs

    Compaction reduces the number of operations to push, saving bandwidth and
    server processing time. Run compaction when:
    - Sync queue exceeds 100 operations
    - Before any sync attempt
    - On app startup (in case the app crashed during compaction)

5.7 CONFLICT RESOLUTION DURING PUSH

    When the client pushes and the server detects a conflict:

    Server response format:
    {
        status: "conflict",
        server_version: { ...full record with server HLC timestamps... },
        client_version: { ...what the client sent... },
        resolution: "server_wins" | "client_wins" | "merged",
        merged_version: { ...if merged... }
    }

    Client handling:
    1. Receive conflict response
    2. Apply merged_version (or server_version) locally
    3. If client had additional local changes not in the push:
       re-merge with the server response using LwwResolver
    4. Update sync queue: mark the conflicted operation as "completed"
    5. If the merge produced new local-winning fields, create a new sync
       queue entry to push those fields

================================================================================
SECTION 6: DATA INTEGRITY GUARANTEES
================================================================================

6.1 HYBRID LOGICAL CLOCK IMPLEMENTATION

    See Section 2.0 for the full HLC algorithm.

    Additional integrity rules:

    - Server MUST validate client HLC wall-time is within MAX_DRIFT of server time
    - Server MUST reject operations with future timestamps (clock manipulation)
    - Server assigns its own HLC to each accepted operation (server HLC is authoritative)
    - Client stores both client_hlc and server_hlc for each field
    - Conflict resolution uses server_hlc (not client_hlc)
    - Client_hlc is retained for debugging and audit purposes only

6.2 SYNC CHECKPOINT / WATERMARK SYSTEM

    Replace the current simple lastSyncTimestamp with a watermark system:

    Watermark structure:
    {
        entity_type: "task",
        last_sync_id: 145823,          -- monotonically increasing server sync ID
        last_sync_hlc: "...",          -- HLC at last successful sync
        last_full_sync: "2026-03-01",  -- when last full sync was performed
        sync_version: 3                -- schema version at time of sync
    }

    Why sync IDs over timestamps:
    - Sync IDs are monotonically increasing integers assigned by the server
    - They provide total ordering (no two operations share the same sync ID)
    - They are immune to clock skew
    - This is how Linear implements it (lastSyncId in their protocol)
    - Timestamps can have duplicates; sync IDs cannot

    Full sync triggers:
    - First-ever sync for a new device
    - Client has not synced in > 90 days (tombstones may have been purged)
    - Schema version mismatch (migrations happened while offline)
    - Client detects data corruption (checksum mismatch)
    - User explicitly requests "Force full sync" from settings

6.3 CHECKSUM VERIFICATION

    Periodic integrity checks between client and server:

    Entity-level checksum:
    - Compute CRC32 of (entity_id + all field values sorted alphabetically + all field HLCs)
    - Store as a computed field on each entity: checksum TEXT
    - When pulling updates, verify checksum matches
    - If mismatch: request full entity from server, replace local version

    Collection-level checksum:
    - For each entity type, compute aggregate checksum:
      XOR of all individual entity checksums for that user
    - Compare client aggregate vs server aggregate during sync
    - If match: no integrity issues, skip detailed check
    - If mismatch: perform entity-by-entity comparison to find diverged records

    Checksum sync protocol:
    1. Client sends: { entity_type: "task", aggregate_checksum: "abc123", count: 47 }
    2. Server computes its own aggregate for that user
    3. If match: respond with { status: "consistent" }
    4. If mismatch: respond with { status: "diverged", entity_checksums: [...] }
    5. Client compares entity-level checksums, requests full records for mismatches

    Frequency: Run checksum verification every 24 hours, or on app startup after
    a crash, or when the user reports "something looks wrong."

6.4 OPERATION ORDERING GUARANTEES

    Causal ordering guarantee:
    If operation A causally precedes operation B (A happened-before B),
    then A's sync ID < B's sync ID on the server.

    How this is enforced:
    - Client includes parent_sync_id in dependent operations
    - Server validates: parent_sync_id must already exist
    - If parent hasn't been processed yet, server queues the child (hold for up to
      30 seconds, then reject with "dependency not found")
    - This prevents a subtask from being created before its parent task exists on
      the server

    Total ordering on the server:
    - Server uses PostgreSQL SERIALIZABLE isolation for sync operations
    - Each accepted operation gets the next sync_id (BIGSERIAL)
    - sync_id is the single source of truth for ordering
    - All clients see operations in the same order

6.5 SCHEMA VERSIONING FOR SYNC COMPATIBILITY

    When the app schema changes (new fields, renamed fields, type changes):

    sync_schema_versions table:
    {
        version: 3,
        introduced_at: "2026-03-15",
        changes: [
            { entity: "task", field: "energy_level", action: "added", default: "medium" },
            { entity: "task", field: "old_field", action: "removed" }
        ]
    }

    Backward compatibility rules:
    - New fields: old clients ignore unknown fields, server applies defaults
    - Removed fields: old clients may still send them, server ignores
    - Type changes: server transforms (e.g., string "3" -> integer 3)
    - Required new fields: server applies default value if old client doesn't send

    Client must send its sync_schema_version with every sync request.
    Server adapts its responses to match the client's version.

6.6 ANTI-ENTROPY REPAIR

    In addition to checksum verification, implement an anti-entropy protocol
    that runs weekly (or on-demand):

    1. Client sends Merkle tree of all entity IDs + HLCs, grouped by entity type
    2. Server computes its own Merkle tree
    3. Trees are compared level by level (efficient O(log n) comparison)
    4. Divergent branches are identified and only those entities are re-synced
    5. This catches any silent data corruption, missed deltas, or sync bugs

    Merkle tree structure:
    - Leaf: hash(entity_id + entity_checksum)
    - Node: hash(left_child + right_child)
    - Root: single hash representing entire dataset

    If Merkle roots match: datasets are identical. Done.
    If roots differ: traverse tree to find divergent leaves in O(log n) comparisons.

================================================================================
SECTION 7: INDUSTRY REFERENCE ANALYSIS
================================================================================

7.1 FIGMA

    Architecture: Property-level LWW with server authority
    Sync: WebSocket, server assigns order, broadcasts to all clients
    Conflict: Each property on each object is an independent LWW register
    Storage: Server holds full state in memory, checkpoints every 30-60 seconds
    Offline: Limited — Figma is primarily online-first
    Delete: Server-authoritative, no client-side delete queue
    Key insight: "It's not about OT vs CRDT — it's about property-level vs
    character-level conflict resolution." UNJYNX should use property-level (field-level).

7.2 LINEAR

    Architecture: Local-first with IndexedDB, server-ordered sync IDs
    Sync: WebSocket for real-time, HTTP for bootstrap and batch
    Conflict: LWW with server-assigned monotonic sync IDs
    Bootstrap: Full dataset download on first connect, then incremental deltas
    Offline: Full offline support — all operations queued locally
    Delete: Soft delete with server-side cascade
    Key insight: Total ordering via sync IDs eliminates distributed consensus complexity.
    Linear proves that a centralized server with LWW is sufficient for B2B collaboration.
    UNJYNX should adopt the sync ID pattern.

7.3 NOTION

    Architecture: Block-based with CRDT migration for offline support
    Sync: WebSocket push-based updates, per-page channel subscriptions
    Conflict: CRDT-based (Peritext for rich text), property-level for metadata
    Offline: SQLite local storage, offline page tree with reason tracking
    Bootstrap: Selective — only pages marked as "available offline" are stored locally
    Reconnection: lastDownloadedTimestamp per page, differential fetch
    Delete: Soft delete with block-level granularity
    Key insight: Notion's offline_page + offline_action tables provide a sophisticated
    model for tracking WHY something is available offline (favorited, auto-downloaded,
    toggled). UNJYNX should track sync scope reasons similarly for team projects.

7.4 TODOIST

    Architecture: Sync token-based incremental protocol
    Sync: HTTP POST to /sync endpoint, no persistent WebSocket for sync
    Conflict: Last-write-wins using timestamps
    Batching: Up to 100 commands per request, processed sequentially
    Idempotency: UUID per command, server rejects duplicate UUIDs
    Temp IDs: Client uses temporary IDs, server returns mapping to permanent IDs
    Delete: Soft delete (is_deleted flag), included in sync responses
    Key insight: Todoist's temp_id_mapping is essential for offline-first apps
    that create entities offline. UNJYNX uses UUIDv7 client-side which avoids
    the need for temp_id mapping (client IDs are the permanent IDs).

7.5 WHAT UNJYNX SHOULD ADOPT FROM EACH

    From Figma:   Field-level (property-level) LWW resolution (ALREADY IMPLEMENTED)
    From Linear:  Server-assigned monotonic sync IDs for total ordering (ADOPT)
    From Linear:  IndexedDB/SQLite local-first with full offline support (ALREADY IMPLEMENTED via Drift)
    From Notion:  Sync scope tracking (offline_action reasons) (ADOPT for team features)
    From Notion:  CRDT for rich text fields only (ADOPT in Phase 3 for task descriptions)
    From Todoist: Command UUID idempotency (ADOPT)
    From Todoist: Batched sync operations (ADOPT)
    From All:     Soft delete as primary deletion mechanism (ADOPT)

